00:10:35,140 --> 00:10:36,980
MAN:
Everybody told me,

265
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:38,970
"Hubert, don't date
someone from work."

266
00:10:39,010 --> 00:10:41,150
But did I listen? No.

267
00:10:41,170 --> 00:10:43,010
Let me tell you something.
She likes to say

268
00:10:43,040 --> 00:10:44,270
I stole her innocence?

269
00:10:44,310 --> 00:10:45,910
Well, what about my innocence?

270
00:10:45,950 --> 00:10:47,120
I was never the same
after we broke up.

271
00:10:47,150 --> 00:10:48,550
ADULT SHELDON:
Two years later,

272
00:10:48,580 --> 00:10:50,810
Mr. Givens became
the high school principal,

273
00:10:50,850 --> 00:10:53,920
which might be why Ms. MacElroy
became morbidly obese.

274
00:10:53,950 --> 00:10:56,450
I had the brains, I had the
charm, and I don't like to brag,

275
00:10:56,490 --> 00:10:58,430
but I was pretty easy
on the eyes back then.

276
00:10:58,460 --> 00:11:00,470
That woman got herself
one heck of a package.

277
00:11:00,490 --> 00:11:02,760
But some people don't
want to be satisfied.

278
00:11:04,100 --> 00:11:06,170
Is that any good?

279
00:11:06,200 --> 00:11:07,840
I'm afraid not.

280
00:11:07,870 --> 00:11:09,880
I failed to make
a single friend.

281
00:11:09,900 --> 00:11:12,570
That sucks. I have a tough time
making friends, too.

282
00:11:12,610 --> 00:11:15,410
The worst part is, it
was important to my mom.

283
00:11:15,440 --> 00:11:18,270
My parents pressure me about
making friends all the time.

284
00:11:18,310 --> 00:11:21,410
So you understand
what I'm going through.

285
00:11:21,450 --> 00:11:24,190
Oh, I read that book.
It's excellent.

286
00:11:24,220 --> 00:11:25,490
Are you into rocketry?

287
00:11:25,520 --> 00:11:28,130
I started with
water propulsion,

288
00:11:28,160 --> 00:11:29,860
worked my way up
to solid fuel,

289
00:11:29,890 --> 00:11:32,450
then went back to water after
I set our garage on fire.

290
00:11:32,490 --> 00:11:35,190
Nice.
I also tried to
get some uranium

291
00:11:35,230 --> 00:11:39,040
and build an atomic engine,
but that stuff's hard to find.

292
00:11:39,070 --> 00:11:41,610
Probably for the best.

293
00:11:41,630 --> 00:11:44,030
Well, good luck on your
quest to find a friend.

294
00:11:44,070 --> 00:11:46,400
You, too.

295
00:11:51,410 --> 00:11:54,880
If you haven't found one
yet, I have good news.

296
00:11:57,220 --> 00:12:00,090
Mom, what do you know
about the drug Prozac?

297
00:12:00,120 --> 00:12:01,350
Not much.

298
00:12:01,390 --> 00:12:04,100
Supposed to make
people happier. Why?

299
00:12:04,120 --> 00:12:05,490
I was just thinking

300
00:12:05,530 --> 00:12:07,900
some of my teachers
might benefit from it.

301
00:12:07,930 --> 00:12:10,340
Speaking of which,

302
00:12:10,360 --> 00:12:12,390
you'll be happy to know
I made a friend today.

303
00:12:12,430 --> 00:12:14,600
Oh.

304
00:12:14,630 --> 00:12:16,400
Well, that's nice.

305
00:12:16,440 --> 00:12:18,880
But, as I said,
this isn't for me.

306
00:12:18,910 --> 00:12:21,310
It's for you.

307
00:12:21,340 --> 00:12:22,600
He made a friend!

308
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:24,210
He did it!

309
00:12:24,240 --> 00:12:26,610
Our little boy has got a friend.

310
00:12:26,650 --> 00:12:28,390
Who is it?
Who cares?

311
00:12:28,420 --> 00:12:30,490
It's a human being.
It's a warm body.

312
00:12:30,520 --> 00:12:32,220
(knocks)
SHELDON:
Mom?

313
00:12:32,250 --> 00:12:33,320
Yes, honey?

314
00:12:33,350 --> 00:12:35,350
Can I come in?
Of course.

315
00:12:35,390 --> 00:12:37,600
Be cool.

316
00:12:37,620 --> 00:12:39,450
What's up, sweetie?
I was wondering

317
00:12:39,490 --> 00:12:42,090
when I could continue
my rocketry hobby.

318
00:12:42,130 --> 00:12:43,970
Uh, Sheldon,
we've been through this.

319
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:46,240
You can build them.
You just can't launch them.

320
00:12:46,270 --> 00:12:48,110
But launching them
is the fun part.

321
00:12:48,140 --> 00:12:49,310
Tell that to the family
of squirrels

322
00:12:49,340 --> 00:12:50,540
who died in the fire.

323
00:12:50,570 --> 00:12:51,730
Okay.

324
00:12:51,770 --> 00:12:54,370
It was just something I was
hoping to do with my new friend.

325
00:12:54,410 --> 00:12:55,580
Hang on.

326
00:12:55,610 --> 00:12:57,050
Uh, yes.

327
00:12:57,080 --> 00:12:58,150
It's fine.

328
00:12:58,180 --> 00:12:59,180
Ban is lifted.

329
00:12:59,210 --> 00:13:00,410
Mary...
It's for his friend.

330
00:13:00,450 --> 00:13:02,450
He's got a friend.

331
00:13:03,520 --> 00:13:04,690
Besides,
those could have been rats.

332
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:06,420
Their bodies
were so badly burned.

333
00:13:06,450 --> 00:13:09,620
I thought we were being cool,
but okay.

334
00:13:09,660 --> 00:13:10,800
Hey, here's an idea.

335
00:13:10,820 --> 00:13:13,960
Why don't you invite your
new buddy over for dinner?

336
00:13:13,990 --> 00:13:15,160
Why?
Well, honey,

337
00:13:15,200 --> 00:13:18,600
um, that is what friends do.

338
00:13:18,630 --> 00:13:20,430
My mother asked
me to ask you

339
00:13:20,470 --> 00:13:22,340
if you'd like to
join us for dinner.

340
00:13:22,370 --> 00:13:26,180
Why?
I was hoping you'd know.

341
00:13:31,480 --> 00:13:33,090
MARY:
He's here!

342
00:13:33,110 --> 00:13:35,710
Everybody, stay calm!
Just a normal day,

343
00:13:35,750 --> 00:13:38,160
just a normal dinner.
MISSY:
Can I eat in front of the TV?

344
00:13:38,190 --> 00:13:40,630
MARY: No, you can eat
in front of Sheldon's friend.

345
00:13:40,650 --> 00:13:42,420
MISSY:
Aw, fudge.
I know what "fudge" means,

346
00:13:42,460 --> 00:13:44,700
and you are right
on the edge, young lady.

347
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:47,560
Welcome.

348
00:13:56,340 --> 00:13:58,080
GEORGE SR.:
So, uh...

349
00:13:58,110 --> 00:14:00,180
Tam. What kind of name is that?

350
00:14:00,210 --> 00:14:01,550
Vietnamese. Sir.

351
00:14:01,570 --> 00:14:04,110
Sure. You know, I spent
a little time over there.

352
00:14:04,140 --> 00:14:06,310
Army.

353
00:14:08,050 --> 00:14:10,190
Your mom's name isn't
Kim-Lee, is it?

354
00:14:10,220 --> 00:14:11,720
No. Sir.

355
00:14:11,750 --> 00:14:13,320
Good.

356
00:14:13,350 --> 00:14:16,180
I mean, you know,
it's a small country.

357
00:14:16,220 --> 00:14:17,490
(chuckles):
So...

358
00:14:17,520 --> 00:14:19,220
Mary, how's that food coming?

359
00:14:19,260 --> 00:14:20,270
MARY:
Almost.

360
00:14:20,290 --> 00:14:22,420
So, Vietnam, like in Rambo.

361
00:14:22,460 --> 00:14:24,590
Yes.
That's a cool movie.

362
00:14:24,630 --> 00:14:25,590
Yes.

363
00:14:25,630 --> 00:14:26,730
Are you in it?

364
00:14:26,770 --> 00:14:28,640
No.
Hmm.

365
00:14:28,670 --> 00:14:32,040
Why would you think
you knew his mom?

366
00:14:32,070 --> 00:14:33,600
MARY:
All right, Tam.

367
00:14:33,640 --> 00:14:36,470
I decided I was gonna make
you a real Texas dinner.

368
00:14:36,510 --> 00:14:38,320
Barbecued chicken and brisket.

369
00:14:38,350 --> 00:14:39,520
Thank you.

370
00:14:39,550 --> 00:14:41,120
Well, I figured
you were probably tired

371
00:14:41,150 --> 00:14:43,060
of stuff wiggling around
on your plate.

372
00:14:43,080 --> 00:14:45,350
Okay, let's say grace.

373
00:14:45,390 --> 00:14:46,620
Now, Tam, when I say "Jesus,"

374
00:14:46,650 --> 00:14:48,780
feel free to say the word
"Buddha" in your head.

375
00:14:48,820 --> 00:14:50,120
I'm actually Catholic.

376
00:14:50,160 --> 00:14:52,660
Oh. Well, that's too bad.

377
00:14:52,690 --> 00:14:54,360
Thank you, God,
for this food,

378
00:14:54,390 --> 00:14:56,720
and bless the hands
that prepared it.

379
00:14:56,760 --> 00:14:59,260
And thank you so much
for Sheldon's new friend.

380
00:14:59,300 --> 00:15:01,510
ALL:
Amen.

381
00:15:01,530 --> 00:15:04,270
So, Tam, tell us
about your family.

382
00:15:04,300 --> 00:15:06,170
What brings y'all to Texas?

383
00:15:06,210 --> 00:15:08,150
Well, after the American War...

384
00:15:08,180 --> 00:15:09,250
You mean the Vietnam War.

385
00:15:09,280 --> 00:15:10,780
We call it the American War.

386
00:15:10,810 --> 00:15:12,370
Hmm.
Anyway,

387
00:15:12,410 --> 00:15:13,740
after the war, my
father was sent

388
00:15:13,780 --> 00:15:15,240
to a reeducation camp

389
00:15:15,280 --> 00:15:16,440
because he fought
on the wrong side.

390
00:15:16,480 --> 00:15:17,510
You mean our side.

391
00:15:17,550 --> 00:15:20,250
I was trying to be nice.

392
00:15:20,290 --> 00:15:21,390
So, for many years,

393
00:15:21,420 --> 00:15:23,190
my mother and my
sisters and I

394
00:15:23,220 --> 00:15:24,690
were very poor

395
00:15:24,720 --> 00:15:27,390
and very often
didn't have much to eat.

396
00:15:27,430 --> 00:15:29,630
Then, when he was released...

397
00:15:29,660 --> 00:15:31,530
What'd they teach him
at the reeducation camp?

398
00:15:31,560 --> 00:15:33,060
How to be a communist.

399
00:15:33,100 --> 00:15:34,800
Cool, like in Rambo.

400
00:15:34,830 --> 00:15:36,100
(chuckles nervously)

401
00:15:36,140 --> 00:15:37,210
When he was released,

402
00:15:37,240 --> 00:15:38,810
we escaped on a small boat

403
00:15:38,840 --> 00:15:42,550
and spent many weeks at sea
dodging Cambodian pirates

404
00:15:42,580 --> 00:15:44,220
until we reached Thailand.

405
00:15:44,240 --> 00:15:47,140
Oh, that's supposed to be
a beautiful country.

406
00:15:47,180 --> 00:15:49,610
Lovely beaches.
TAM:
I wouldn't know.

407
00:15:49,650 --> 00:15:51,760
We were forced to live
in a refugee camp,

408
00:15:51,780 --> 00:15:55,220
where the only thing we had
to eat were pigeons and rats.

409
00:15:55,260 --> 00:15:57,560
Ha! That's a job for hot sauce.

410
00:15:58,630 --> 00:16:00,430
Finally,

411
00:16:00,460 --> 00:16:02,290
we were allowed
to come to United States

412
00:16:02,330 --> 00:16:03,700
and start over in Galveston.

413
00:16:03,730 --> 00:16:06,660
My father saved money
and bought his own shrimp boat.

414
00:16:06,700 --> 00:16:09,510
There's a happy ending. Huh?

415
00:16:09,540 --> 00:16:11,640
See, kids?
When the going gets tough,

416
00:16:11,670 --> 00:16:13,840
America provides.
TAM:
It did.

417
00:16:13,870 --> 00:16:16,570
Until the Ku Klux Klan
burned our boat

418
00:16:16,610 --> 00:16:18,450
and chased us away.

419
00:16:18,480 --> 00:16:21,150
You gonna put a good spin
on that one?

420
00:16:21,180 --> 00:16:23,310
So we came to Medford

421
00:16:23,350 --> 00:16:24,680
and opened up
a convenience store.

422
00:16:24,720 --> 00:16:27,330
My parents work 16 hours a day,

423
00:16:27,350 --> 00:16:29,150
seven days a week

424
00:16:29,190 --> 00:16:31,500
for very little money.

425
00:16:36,260 --> 00:16:38,660
Well, that was depressing.

426
00:16:44,770 --> 00:16:47,170
I don't understand
why it didn't launch.

427
00:16:47,210 --> 00:16:48,480
Me, neither.

428
00:16:48,510 --> 00:16:51,450
Evil Nazi scientists
did it 50 years ago.

429
00:16:51,480 --> 00:16:53,190
How hard could it be?

430
00:16:53,210 --> 00:16:54,410
(doorbell rings)

431
00:16:57,450 --> 00:16:59,310
Can I help you?

432
00:16:59,350 --> 00:17:01,650
Sorry to bother you, ma'am. FBI.

433
00:17:01,690 --> 00:17:03,800
We're looking
for a Sheldon Lee Cooper.

434
00:17:03,820 --> 00:17:05,650
George!

435
00:17:05,690 --> 00:17:07,190
GEORGE SR.:
I'm on the can.

436
00:17:07,230 --> 00:17:09,400
Now!
(door opens)

437
00:17:09,430 --> 00:17:12,500
What?
These gentlemen

438
00:17:12,530 --> 00:17:15,200
are with the FBI.
They want to talk to Sheldon.

439
00:17:15,240 --> 00:17:16,810
What?

440
00:17:16,840 --> 00:17:18,410
We... Uh...

441
00:17:18,440 --> 00:17:19,940
Y-You fellas
must have made a mistake.

442
00:17:19,970 --> 00:17:21,500
Sheldon's nine.

443
00:17:21,540 --> 00:17:22,800
Well, someone living
at this address

444
00:17:22,840 --> 00:17:25,370
recently called a mining
operation in Canada

445
00:17:25,410 --> 00:17:26,510
and tried to buy uranium.

446
00:17:26,550 --> 00:17:29,220
Okay, maybe it's not a mistake.

447
00:17:29,250 --> 00:17:30,490
It's ridiculous.

448
00:17:30,520 --> 00:17:31,790
Let's just go talk to him.

449
00:17:31,820 --> 00:17:32,720
Huh?

450
00:17:32,750 --> 00:17:34,420
He's just a little,
itty-bitty thing.

451
00:17:34,450 --> 00:17:35,680
Really, he's harmless.

452
00:17:38,630 --> 00:17:40,530
SHELDON:
Sorry!

453
00:17:40,560 --> 00:17:43,190
He's in the garage.

